# Lambda LAP — Cursor Rules

## Project Context

Lambda LAP is a full-stack educational platform (SigmaLoop) for learning programming with interactive code execution, courses, challenges, and AI mentorship.

## Repository Layout

- `Backend/` — Node.js + Express v5 + TypeScript API (MongoDB/Mongoose)
- `Frontend/` — React 19 + TypeScript + Vite SPA (Tailwind CSS)
- `Graduation Project/` — Design reference only (API contract, DB schema, UI mockups, Next.js prototype). Do NOT modify for implementation.

## Tech Stack

### Backend
- Express v5.2.1, Mongoose v8.8.4, JWT auth (jsonwebtoken + bcryptjs)
- Entry: `Backend/src/server.ts` → `Backend/src/app.ts`
- API base: `http://localhost:4000/api/v1`
- Response format: JSend (`{ success: true, data: {...} }`)
- MVC pattern: models/ → controllers/ → routes/

### Frontend
- React 19, Vite 7.2.4, React Router DOM v7, Axios, Monaco Editor
- Entry: `Frontend/src/main.tsx` → `Frontend/src/App.tsx`
- Auth: Context API (AuthContext.tsx), JWT in localStorage
- Styling: Tailwind CSS with glass morphism utilities

## Code Style

### Backend
- ESLint Standard + TypeScript, Prettier: single quotes, no trailing commas, 100 char width
- Files: camelCase for utils, PascalCase for models
- Always use JSend helpers from `src/utils/jsend.ts` for responses

### Frontend
- ESLint recommended + TypeScript, Prettier: double quotes, trailing commas es5, 80 char width
- Components: PascalCase.tsx, services: camelCase.ts
- Always use the shared Axios instance from `src/services/api.ts`

## Conventions

1. Use TypeScript strict mode — no `any` types unless absolutely necessary
2. API responses always use JSend format via `success()` and `error()` helpers
3. Auth middleware pattern: `authenticate` → `authorize('ROLE1', 'ROLE2')`
4. New endpoints follow: Model → Controller → Route → Register in routes/index.ts
5. New pages follow: Page component → Route in App.tsx → Nav link if needed
6. UI components in `Frontend/src/components/ui/` are reusable primitives — no business logic
7. Page sub-components live alongside their page (e.g., `pages/Lesson/components/`)

## Database Models

User, Course, Lesson, Challenge, Enrollment, LessonProgress, Submission, ChatThread, ChatMessage

## Supported Languages (for challenges)

Python, C++, Java, JavaScript, TypeScript, Go, Rust

## Known Gaps to Be Aware Of

- Code execution controller returns mock/dummy results — sandbox not yet integrated
- Rate limiting middleware exists but is disabled (pass-through)
- Frontend API URL is hardcoded (no .env usage)
- Admin routes lack role-specific guards
- No input validation library (Joi/Zod) — controllers validate manually
- Chat/mentorship AI integration is pending
